        <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Dog Training Activities & Tips</h2>
        <div class="container dog-training-section mt-5">
            <!-- Basic Comands-->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Basic Commands</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Focus and Attention:</strong> Start each session by teaching your dog to focus on
                            you, using commands like “look” or “watch me.” This helps keep their attention during
                            training.</li>
                        <li><strong>Gradual Increase in Difficulty:</strong> Begin training in a quiet environment with
                            minimal distractions, gradually moving to busier settings as your dog becomes more
                            consistent.</li>
                        <li><strong>Consistency is Key:</strong> Use the same word, tone, and hand gesture for each
                            command to prevent confusion and ensure your dog associates the command with a specific
                            action.</li>
                        <li><strong>Short Commands:</strong> Keep commands simple and one-worded; avoid lengthy phrases
                            that might confuse your dog.</li>
                        <li><strong>Reward Immediately:</strong> Deliver treats or praise right after the dog performs
                            the desired action. Timing is crucial to help them make the connection.</li>
                        <li><strong>Release Command:</strong> Teach a release word, like “okay” or “free,” to let your
                            dog know when the command is complete. This is especially helpful for commands like “stay.”
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/sit.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Basic Commands">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- leash training-->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Leash Training</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Reward Good Behavior:</strong> Reward your dog whenever they walk with a loose
                            leash. Small, frequent treats work well to reinforce this behavior.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use a “Turn and Walk” Technique:</strong> When your dog pulls, turn and walk in the
                            opposite direction. This encourages them to pay attention to your movements and follow your
                            lead.</li>
                        <li><strong>Start Indoors or in a Quiet Area:</strong> Begin leash training in a calm, familiar
                            space with minimal distractions to help your dog focus on following you.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use Positive Reinforcement:</strong> Reward your dog with treats and praise when
                            they stay by your side without pulling, reinforcing that staying close is a good behavior.
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Choose the Right Equipment:</strong> Use a comfortable harness or collar and a
                            sturdy leash. Avoid retractable leashes for training as they can encourage pulling.</li>
                        <li><strong>Teach the “Heel” Command:</strong> Introduce the “heel” command to signal your dog
                            to stay beside you. Use this word consistently during training.</li>
                        <li><strong>Stop When They Pull:</strong> Each time your dog starts pulling, stop walking
                            immediately. Resume walking only when the leash is relaxed, teaching them that pulling won't
                            get them anywhere.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/lead.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="lead training">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Recall Training-->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Recall Training (Come When Called)</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Start with Short Distances:</strong> Begin with short recall exercises at a few feet
                            away, and increase the distance as your dog gets comfortable responding.</li>
                        <li><strong>Choose a Unique Recall Cue:</strong> Use a specific word like “come” or a unique
                            sound, such as a whistle, to signal your dog to return. Keep this cue consistent to avoid
                            confusion.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use a Long Leash for Safety:</strong> In open or outdoor spaces, use a long training
                            leash to give your dog freedom while maintaining control and reinforcing recall.</li>
                        <li><strong>Make It Fun and Engaging:</strong> Call your dog in an enthusiastic, upbeat tone to
                            make coming back feel exciting. Clap, crouch down, or show a toy if it helps catch their
                            attention.</li>
                        <li><strong>Practice in Different Environments:</strong> Once your dog is reliably coming in a
                            familiar setting, practice in other locations to help them generalize the behavior.</li>
                        <li><strong>Reward Immediately and Generously:</strong> Give treats, praise, or their favorite
                            toy as soon as they reach you. Rewards should be immediate to reinforce the behavior.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/recall.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Reacall Commands">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!--Impulse Control-->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Impulse Control Games</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Start with Simple Exercises:</strong> Begin by asking your dog to “wait” before
                            meals or treats, gradually extending the duration to build patience.</li>
                        <li><strong>Reward Calm Behavior in Exciting Situations:</strong> If they remain calm around new
                            people or pets, offer treats to reinforce their self-control.</li>
                        <li><strong>Practice “Leave It” with Tempting Objects:</strong> Place a treat on the floor and
                            use the “leave it” command, rewarding them only when they ignore the treat until you give
                            permission.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use a Gentle, Consistent Tone:</strong> Keep your commands calm and steady to help
                            your dog focus, especially when they're excited.</li>
                        <li><strong>Introduce the “Take It” Command:</strong> After practicing “leave it,” add a “take
                            it” command to let them know when they can have the treat. This helps reinforce patience and
                            clarity.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use Toys as Impulse Control Practice:</strong> Ask your dog to “wait” before you
                            throw a toy. Gradually increase the waiting time before releasing them to retrieve it.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/impulse.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Impulse Commands">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Toys -->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Interactive Toys & Puzzles</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Start with Simple Puzzles:</strong> Begin with easy puzzle toys that require minimal
                            effort to solve, gradually increasing difficulty as your dog gains confidence.</li>
                        <li><strong>Rotate Between Types of Toys:</strong> Alternate between food-dispensing balls,
                            interactive puzzles, and treat-stuffed toys to maintain variety and prevent boredom.</li>
                        <li><strong>Supervise Initial Play:</strong> Watch them as they figure out new toys to ensure
                            safety and guide them if they get frustrated or confused.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use Treats as Motivation:</strong> Fill toys with high-value treats or kibble to
                            make the game more rewarding and encourage their engagement.</li>
                        <li><strong>Encourage Independent Play:</strong> Puzzle toys are great for teaching your dog to
                            play independently, which can reduce separation anxiety over time.</li>
                        <li><strong>Incorporate Learning Commands:</strong> Use toys to practice commands like “find it”
                            and “drop it,” adding a training element to playtime.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/interactiveToy.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Interactive Toys">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Social -->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Socialisation Exercises</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Start Early (If Possible):</strong> Begin socialization as early as possible,
                            especially in puppies, as it's easier for them to adjust to new experiences during their
                            formative weeks.</li>
                        <li><strong>Introduce Gradually:</strong> Start with calm environments and familiar people
                            before moving to busier, more stimulating settings, to avoid overwhelming your dog.</li>
                        <li><strong>Vary Locations and Situations:</strong> Expose your dog to different settings like
                            parks, busy streets, car rides, and quiet neighborhoods to build confidence in various
                            environments.</li>
                        <li><strong>Teach Body Language Awareness:</strong> Pay attention to your dog's body language to
                            understand their comfort level, adjusting the environment or distance if they show signs of
                            stress.</li>
                        <li><strong>Socialise in Different Weather Conditions:</strong> Take your dog out in different
                            weather (rain, snow, wind) so they become comfortable with various elements.</li>
                        <li><strong>Observe and Respect Boundaries:</strong> Watch for any signs of discomfort, such as
                            tail tucking or avoiding eye contact, and remove them from the situation if they seem
                            overwhelmed.</li>
                        <li><strong>Vary Your Walking Routes:</strong> Regularly change your walking path to expose them
                            to different sights, smells, and people, enriching their daily experiences.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/socialise.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Socialising">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Training Place Command-->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Training “Place” Command</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Choose a Consistent Spot:</strong> Designate a specific area, like a mat, bed, or
                            crate, and use it consistently so your dog associates it with the “place” command.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use Clear Visual Cues:</strong> Stand near the spot and point to it when saying
                            “place” to help your dog understand where to go.</li>
                        <li><strong>Start with Short Durations:</strong> Begin by having your dog stay in their
                            designated spot for a few seconds before releasing them, gradually extending the time as
                            they improve.</li>
                        <li><strong>Incorporate Rewards:</strong> Reward your dog with treats, praise, or a favorite toy
                            when they successfully go to their place and stay there.</li>
                        <li><strong>Add a Release Cue:</strong> Use a release word like “okay” or “free” to signal when
                            they're allowed to leave the spot, helping them understand they should stay until given
                            permission.</li>
                        <li><strong>Introduce Distractions Slowly:</strong> Gradually add mild distractions, like other
                            people or toys, and reward them for staying in place to build focus.</li>
                        <li><strong>Practice “Place” with Different Rooms:</strong> Encourage your dog to go to their
                            place in various rooms around the house to generalize the behaviour.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/bed.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Place Commands">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Loose-lead walking -->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Loose-Lead Walking</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Use a Shorter Leash:</strong> A shorter leash helps maintain control without
                            allowing your dog too much distance, which can encourage pulling.</li>
                        <li><strong>Start Indoors or in Low-Distraction Areas:</strong> Begin training at home or in a
                            quiet area to teach the basics before progressing to more distracting environments.</li>
                        <li><strong>Practice “Heel” Position:</strong> Teach your dog to walk beside you in the “heel”
                            position. You can use treats or a favorite toy to lure them to your side.</li>
                        <li><strong>Reward Frequently:</strong> Initially, reward every few steps they take by your side
                            without pulling. Gradually increase the number of steps as they improve.</li>
                        <li><strong>Incorporate a Cue Word:</strong> Use a consistent phrase like “let's go” to signal
                            when to start walking, helping them understand they should follow your pace.</li>
                        <li><strong>Stop When They Pull:</strong> If they begin to pull, stop immediately and wait for
                            them to relax the tension. Resume walking only when the leash is loose to discourage
                            pulling.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/looseLead.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Loose lead walking">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Trick Training-->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Trick Training</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Start with Simple Tricks:</strong> Begin with easy tricks like “shake” or “high
                            five” to build confidence before moving on to more complex ones.</li>
                        <li><strong>Break Down Complex Tricks:</strong> For tricks like “roll over,” teach it in small
                            steps (e.g., lying down first) so your dog can understand each part.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use High-Value Rewards:</strong> Keep your dog motivated by using treats they love
                            or a favorite toy as a reward for each successful step.</li>
                        <li><strong>Incorporate Hand Signals:</strong> Combine verbal cues with hand signals to
                            strengthen their understanding. Over time, they may even respond to just the hand signal.
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Practice Short Sessions:</strong> Keep training sessions short (5-10 minutes) to
                            prevent boredom. Frequent, short sessions are often more effective than long ones.</li>
                        <li><strong>Add Variety:</strong> Switch up the tricks you're working on to keep things fresh
                            and exciting, especially if your dog is quick to learn.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use a Marker Word:</strong> Choose a word like “yes” or use a clicker to mark the
                            exact moment they perform the trick, reinforcing the behavior.</li>
                        <li><strong>End on a High Note:</strong> Always finish a session with a trick they know well to
                            end positively, keeping them excited for the next session.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/cocker.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Basic Commands">
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Hide-and-Seek -->
            <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Hide-and-Seek</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Start with Simple Hiding Spots:</strong> Begin by hiding in easy, visible spots to
                            help your dog understand the game. Gradually move to more challenging locations as they get
                            the hang of it.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use a Familiar Cue:</strong> Use cues like “come find me” or “where am I?” so your
                            dog associates these words with the game.</li>
                        <li><strong>Add Rewards for Finding You:</strong> Give treats or lots of praise each time they
                            find you to reinforce their effort and make it more exciting.</li>
                        <li><strong>Involve a Family Member or Friend:</strong> Take turns hiding so your dog can learn
                            to locate different people, strengthening their social and recall skills.</li>
                        <li><strong>Vary the Locations:</strong> Change hiding spots to keep the game fresh and
                            encourage your dog to really search for you.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use Scent as a Hint:</strong> Rub your hands on a toy or treat and leave it near
                            your hiding spot to give them a scent clue, helping them build scent-tracking skills.</li>
                        <li><strong>Encourage Nose Work:</strong> Ask your dog to sniff around and follow their nose to
                            locate you, which strengthens their natural tracking ability.</li>
                        <li><strong>Play Outside for Extra Challenge:</strong> Try playing in the garden or a fenced
                            area to add natural distractions, helping your dog focus even in a new environment.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
                    <img src="~/images/training/hide.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Basic Commands">
                </div>
            </div>
    </section>
